// The Alchemist's Handbook: Manual for Practical Laboratory Alchemy

== The Alchemist's Handbook
_by Frater Albertus (Dr. Albert Reidel)_

#hm-note[
  Frater Albertus (Albert Reidel) founded the Paracelsus Research Society (PRS) in Salt Lake City, Utah in 1960, later accredited as Paracelsus College. This handbook — first published 1960, revised 1974 — was the seminal text that revived practical laboratory alchemy in the 20th century. Israel Regardie, who wrote the foreword, said: "There is no other book that I have ever encountered in all my long years in this movement that is one fraction as clear or as helpful." Robert Bartlett studied under Albertus at the PRS from 1974 onward and served as Chief Chemist at Paralab. The book is explicitly a description of the *Lesser Circulation* (herbal work). The *Greater Circulation* (metallic work) is not given — "it is not permissible" — but mastering the herbal process opens the gate to it.
]

=== Foreword (by Israel Regardie)

#doctrine[
  "The fundamental process is so simple that even women and children could accomplish it... It requires effort, labor and prayer — or its equivalents — to achieve the simple child-like state capable of achieving the goals of alchemy." — Regardie
]

- "Alchemy as Science and Art provided both a means to synthesize all the other sciences and a training of the intellectual and spiritual faculties." — Bonus of Ferrara (~1310), calling alchemy "the key of all good things, the Art of Art, the Science of Sciences."
- Regardie's central testimony: He had originally argued all alchemy was psycho-spiritual (in his 1938 book *The Philosopher's Stone*). After studying practical laboratory alchemy at the PRS under Frater Albertus, he recanted publicly in his second edition: "It took no more than a few minutes to help me realize how presumptuous I had been to assert dogmatically that all alchemy was psycho-spiritual."
- *Ora et labora* (pray and work) — but above all, *work*. Without it, you cannot even begin.


=== Chapter I: Introduction to Alchemy

==== The Core Definition

#doctrine[
  "What is Alchemy? This question can be answered to the satisfaction of the inquiring mind. What, then, is Alchemy? It is *the raising of vibrations.*"
]

- Alchemy is *Evolution* — helping nature bring her products to perfection. Nature does not resent an artificial shortcut, provided it works within natural law. Planting in warmth in winter is not contrary to nature; it is in harmony with natural laws.
- The life force is *not* contained in Fire, Earth, Air, and Water. It is a separate essence filling the universe — the *Quintessence*, the fifth of the four. The alchemist's primary task is to find and then separate this fifth essence.
- What the extracted Quintessence looks like when it first appears: a dense smoke-like vapor that settles (after passing through a condenser) into a water-like substance of yellowish color carrying an oily tinge — the Alchemical Sulfur.
- Alchemy is a *life's work*. "One earthly incarnation in many, if not most, cases is an insufficient time for the full completion of the work."

==== The Prerequisite: Cleansing

- "If it were not for the cleansing, purging, and aging of the alchemist-to-be over a great length of time, like the *subjectum* he is working with, how could it be kept from the profane and the unworthy? Only that which has stood the test of fire has been purified."
- The alchemist's aims: to help relieve suffering mankind in its physical and spiritual misery. Personal greed has no place in Alchemy. Non-acceptance of this excludes one automatically from the circle of Adepts.
- "When the pupil is ready, the Master will appear." One may search and study hard, yet it takes more than study. *An honest heart, a clean heart, a true heart, a benevolent and contrite heart accomplishes more than all book learning.*

==== The Seed: Secret of Creation

- "Since everything that grows comes from a seed, the fruit must be contained in its seed. Mark this well, for *here lies the secret of creation.*"
- Herbs, animals, minerals and metals all grow from seed. Understanding this secret — only partly revealed to mankind generally — constitutes the main theoretical subject in Alchemy.
- The *Quintessence* (fifth essence) is the truly important object the alchemist seeks. After its separation, the answer to what lies behind the secret of creation manifests.

==== The Seven Rosicrucian Concepts (from Thor Kiimaletho)
_(Quoted from an extra-curricular lecture at the Rose Croix University)_

1. The Origin of the Universe is Divine. The Universe is a manifestation and emanation from the One Absolute Cosmic Being. There is but One Life in the Universe — the Universal Life. It saturates and fills all forms, shapes, and manifestations.
2. The soul is a spark of divine consciousness. As a drop of water is part of the ocean, so the soul manifesting in material expression is part of the One Soul. In the human being it develops the personality and individual expression.
3. The soul-force possesses potentially the powers of the divine principle at work in the universe. Since one incarnation cannot be sufficient, the personality must return again and again to achieve maximum development.
4. The moral law (Karma / cause and effect) is one of the basic laws of the universe. It works impersonally like any law of nature. "As the fruit is contained in the seed, so the consequences are inherent in the act." Knowledge of this gives man the power to control his own destiny.
5. Life has a purpose. Happiness is a real thing and is a by-product of knowledge, action, and living.
6. Man has free choice. He has tremendous powers of both good and evil depending upon his conscious realizations.
7. Since the individual soul is part of the universal soul, man has access to powers he does not yet know, but which time and knowledge and experience will gradually reveal.


=== Chapter II: The Lesser Circulation

#doctrine[
  "In Alchemy there are the lesser and greater circulations. The former pertains to the herbal kingdom and the latter to the most coveted of them all, the mineral (metallic) realm. A correct *understanding*, and not just knowledge, of the herbal process will open the gate to the great Arcanum."
]

- The Grand Arcanum (complete description of the Greater Circulation) is not given in this book — "It is not permissible." But he who masters the herbal process described here *can* accomplish the Grand Arcanum, if he is ready.
- PATIENCE: "This word should be painted in large letters and then hung above the alchemist's *Athanor*." (Athanor = the oven in which the fire is kept burning, a term used by Paracelsus.)

==== How to Collect and Prepare Plants

- *Barks:* Peel from young trees in autumn or early spring. Shave off the outer portion. Cut thinly; dry in the shade.
- *Roots:* Dig after leaves are dead in the fall (all strength gone into the root) or in early spring before the sap rises.
- *Seeds and Flowers:* Only after fully ripened / in full bloom. Dry quickly in the shade.
- *Medicinal Plants:* While in blossom for best results; can be gathered any time before frost. Dry quickly in the shade.
- *Leaves:* While the plant is in flower. Dry quickly.
- *Fruits and Berries:* When fully ripe. Dry quickly.
- Best drying method: spread thinly on clean paper on the floor where a constant stream of fresh air can pass.
- Storage: herbs in a dry, dark place. Tin cans for powders. Roots in covered boxes. Tinctures and extracts in dark glass bottles.

#hm-note[
  Note: The progressive student will learn later at *what planetary times* herbs should be gathered.
]

==== The Three Kingdoms: A Crucial Principle

- The Quintessence (Mercury) is the same in *all* plant life — universal within the vegetable kingdom. It is also universal in the animal kingdom, and universal in the mineral kingdom. However, although the Mercury is of the same origin, it vibrates differently in each realm:
  - *Vegetable kingdom:* a certain vibration.
  - *Animal kingdom:* a higher vibratory rate.
  - *Mineral realm:* a still higher rate.

#doctrine[
  "*Substances (Essence and Salt) should not be intermixed when elixirs or alchemical medications are prepared.* A common error that has been and is still being made is the intermixing of vegetable essence with animal or mineral salts. Since each constitutes a separate sphere or vibratory group, a mixture of these not properly attuned recipients will produce no manifestation."
]

- Summary of the five key principles:
  1. Three kingdoms: Vegetable, Animal, Mineral.
  2. Each kingdom has its own Mercury — all from the same original source but at different vibrations in each realm.
  3. The Salt of each vegetable manifestation differs from one plant to another. Same holds for all animal and mineral Salts.
  4. Substances (Essence and Salt) should NOT be intermixed between kingdoms when preparing elixirs.
  5. Alchemical elixirs are not products of natural formation but of *artificial production*. Nature alone does not produce the Philosopher's Stone in the same sense that it forms crystals.

- Man, as the highest specimen of the animal realm, can eat from both the vegetable and animal kingdoms and thus can be cured with both. But the most potent form of terrestrial manifestation is produced from the salts and essences from the minerals and metals — in its highest form (brought to perfection only by man) this is the Philosopher's Stone.

==== The Triangle of Manifestation

#doctrine[
  Albertus presents a visual principle: Perfect Medicine (Manifestation) stands at the apex; Positive Force (Essence) on the left; Negative or Properly Attuned Passive Recipient (Salt) on the right. *Both must be present, from the same kingdom, for manifestation to occur.*
]

- In herbal work, the *Sulfur is NOT separated from the Mercury* — they are combined as one liquid in the extract. Only in the mineral work is the separation of Sulfur from Mercury essential. The beginner uses Mercury + Sulfur combined, and Salt separately. These are then joined to produce the alchemical medicine.

==== Three Methods of Extraction

1. *Maceration:* Fresh or dried herb soaked in a solvent (water, alcohol, or ether) and left standing at room temperature.
2. *Circulation (Reflux):* Fresh or dried herb circulated / percolated. A condenser over the flask lets moisture condense and drip back down — continuous cycle. Also called *reflux*.
3. *Extraction (Soxhlet or other apparatus):* Fresh or dried herb placed in a thimble for automated extraction.

- To obtain *all* possible essence, including the oily substance inherent in the herb, the Soxhlet or extraction apparatus method is preferable.
- *Water, Alcohol, or Ether* may be used as the extraction menstruum.

==== Rectification of Alcohol

#lab[
  *First Method (Old Way — Seven Distillations):*
  1. Take any pure non-poisonous alcohol (190 proof spirits) and distil at ≤78°C. Do not use anything that distils above 78°C.
  2. Take the distillate and redistil at ~76°C. Collect what comes over. Repeat — a total of *seven distillations* from the first.
  3. What remains behind will become darker after each distillation.
  4. At the final (7th) distillation the distillate will be a *crystal clear* alcohol.
  5. *Never use methanol (denatured/wood alcohol).*

  *Second Method (Modern/K₂CO₃ Method):*
  1. Distil non-poisonous 190 proof alcohol at 78°C.
  2. To every 1000 ml of this distilled alcohol add *25 grams of potassium carbonate anhydrous* (K₂CO₃). Let stand 48 hours, shaking occasionally. The K₂CO₃ absorbs the remaining water.
  3. Redistil the alcohol at 76°C.
  4. The distillate will be a rectified alcohol.
]

#hm-note[
  *On the source of the alcohol:* Albertus is emphatic that the *Spirit of Wine* obtained from *grape wine* (brandy) is the best and most ripened essence of the vegetable kingdom, claimed to have the *highest vibratory rate* of any essence in the vegetable kingdom, and is therefore the preferred menstruum. *The wine should be pure, unfortified.* Any wine containing more than 17% alcohol by volume may have been fortified with alcohol derived from non-grape sources. When such wine is distilled, the distillate will not be pure Spirits of Wine. Therefore: obtain spirits of wine only from wine containing less than 17% alcohol by volume, or from pure *grape brandy*. This is of great importance in Alchemy. The rectified alcohol used for herbal extraction must undergo yet another preparation before it is fit for *mineral* extractions.
]


=== Chapter III: The Herbal Elixir

==== Soxhlet Extraction (Technical Method)

#lab[
  *Apparatus (3 parts):*
  - Flask (bottom) — half-filled with rectified spirit of wine.
  - Extractor with thimble (middle) — thimble is a filter-paper cylinder containing the finely ground, dried herb.
  - Condenser (top) — cooled with water.

  *Process:*
  1. Grind dried herb to fine powder in a mortar. Place into the thimble.
  2. Attach flask with rectified spirit of wine. Light the fire under the flask. Prefer a *water bath* over an open flame to prevent scorching/burning of the delicate Sulfur (oil) in the extract.
  3. After 3–4 extractions, the alcohol in the flask will become deeply colored. If a dark rim forms on the flask, *lower the fire* immediately.
  4. Completion: when the alcohol coming through the siphon tube eventually runs *crystal clear*, the extraction is complete — all Sulfur and Mercury have been extracted.
  5. Remove the thimble; place the extracted herb residue (feces / *Caput Mortuum*) in an earthenware or porcelain dish.

  *Calcination of the Feces:*
  - Light the residue (saturated with alcohol, it ignites immediately). Burn to black ash — *Nigredo*.
  - Grind the black ash; calcine further until light gray. A prolonged calcination can change the gray to *reddish* color, which is preferable but requires a long time.

  *Cohobation / First Reunion:*
  - Place the calcined ash (Salt) into the lower flask. Pour enough of the extract (Mercury + Sulfur) over this Salt. Reattach to apparatus; begin circulation.
  - The Salt will *feed* on the extract. Continue until the extract in the flask becomes lighter. When there is no further change in color, the Salt has absorbed all it can.
  - If the extract becomes clear, pour it out and add more of the extract until the Salt will absorb no more.
  - Detach flask; remove contents. This is now the *alchemical elixir in its first state* — warm: an oily substance that will run; cold: solid.

  *Increasing Potency:*
  - Calcine the elixir in a calcining dish. Return to extraction apparatus. Circulate again with more of the extracted essence. *Each time this is done, the potency increases.*
]

==== Maceration (Simple Method — No Apparatus Needed)

#lab[
  This method was originally described in the Alchemical Laboratory Bulletin, 1st Quarter No. 1, 1960.

  1. Place the ground dried herb in a glass flask or container that can be well closed.
  2. Pour strong alcohol (*never* denatured alcohol or methanol) or preferably *brandy* over the ground herb.
  3. Close tightly. Place near the furnace (top of water heater, etc.). Temperature must not exceed that required for hatching chicken eggs (~38°C / 100°F). Leave *one-half to one-third* of the container empty above the menstruum for expansion.
  4. After several days, the menstruum will be colored green (shade varies with the herb and quality of alcohol).
  5. When sufficiently macerated, pour the liquid off into a clean glass container.
  6. Place the remaining herbal substance (feces) in a calcining dish. The alcohol-saturated herb will ignite immediately and burn to black ashes. Perform *outside* due to smoke and odor.
  7. Calcine the black ashes: incinerate in any fire-resistant dish, grinding occasionally, until they become a light gray (*calcination*).
  8. While still warm, place the gray ash into a *preheated* flask (to prevent breakage from temperature shock). Pour the previously saved macerate essence over the warm ash. Stopper tightly — no alcohol fumes can escape.
  9. Digest (moderate heat) for about *two weeks*. The Salt will absorb the Essence.
  10. The medication is then ready for use.

  *Dosage:* A few grains of Salt dissolved with a teaspoon of the liquid Essence in a glass of distilled water. *The elixir should never be consumed undiluted.* Two or three tablespoons taken at hourly intervals as needed. Absolutely harmless but of high potency.
]

==== The Vegetable Stone

- The process can be taken further: place the three combined substances (Salt + Mercury + Sulfur) in a tightly sealed glass flask; subject to moderate heat for digestion. In this way a *"stone" in the vegetable kingdom* can be produced.
- "This must not be confused with the Philosopher's Stone."
- The potency of such a stone is far greater than any elixir. This herbal stone will attract the Essence, Sulfur, and Salt of *other herbs* by immersion only (without any further preparation needed from those herbs).

==== The German Spagyric Method (from Grossman, 1922)

#lab[
  1. Take 50 lbs of fresh, flowering plant (including root, stem, leaves, and seeds). Clean, wash, and cut into small pieces.
  2. Pour water over and slowly distil. Separate any essential oil from the water; keep aside.
  3. Return the water (without oil) back over the plant. Add 1–2 spoons of yeast. Place in a wooden container and slightly cover — allow to ferment. Watch carefully; when fermentation ceases, stir well.
  4. Place in a distillation flask and distil until nothing more comes over (steam distillation is best). Calcine the residue remaining in the flask. Leach out with water; filter; slowly evaporate the filtrate. Save the residue (Salt).
  5. Reduce the distillate by further distillation until 2 parts distillate to 1 part leached-out salt. Distil both together once more. Add the oil from Step 2.
  - *Dr. Zimpel's method (alternative):* After fermentation, carefully distil the formed alcohol. Dry and calcine the residue; leach the calcined salt with the first distillate. Filter this liquor (contains soluble minerals, essence, and volatile oil). "The longer it is left undisturbed before using, the better — like wine ripen in the bottle."
]


=== Chapter IV: Medicinal Uses

==== Principles of Dosage

- Alchemical elixirs (combination of Essence, Sulfur and Salt) are the subject — not single tinctures or salts.
- Each repetition of calcination and coagulation after the first state increases the potency.
- *Never* take full strength in large amounts. Due to condensed potency and accelerated vibratory rate, must be taken *greatly diluted* — a few grains dissolved in a glassful of distilled water or pure unadulterated red wine. Two or three tablespoons taken at hourly intervals.
- If the basic medication prescribed is a poisonous one (e.g., a sedative acting as an opiate rather than a curative agent), do not use it.
- If herbal elixirs do not cure the ailment, it is an indication that a higher vibration of medication is required — from outside the herbal realm.
- Fresh air, normal physical exercise, proper food, adequate clothing, and satisfactory sanitary conditions are equally essential for curative purposes.

==== The Copper Plate Test (Validation of the Elixir or Stone)

#lab[
  Before administering any alchemical medication to animals or sick individuals, perform this test:
  1. Heat a *thin, polished sheet of copper* until hot (but not glowing).
  2. Place a small amount of the prepared herbal substance on the plate.
  3. *Pass:* If the medication melts instantly like wax, flows without smoking, and leaves no stain when wiped away when cold — it is correctly prepared.
  4. *Fail:* If it smokes, it is not yet properly fixed and requires further work.
]

==== Clinical Account (Personal)

Albertus recounts: a baby suffering from severe colic was unresponsive to constant medical care from an allopathic physician and surgeon. After administering an alchemical preparation made from the *flowers of chamomile*, the child was cured within a few hours, with no recurrence. He includes this only to demonstrate the harmless nature of properly administered herbal preparations, even to infants.

==== Comparison of Therapeutic Systems

- *Allopathic:* Uses tinctures or salts (alkaloids). Only works with isolated constituents.
- *Homeopathic:* Uses salts (minerals triturated) on the principle *similia similibus curantur* (like cures like).
- *Biochemic (Schuessler):* Replenishes missing minerals in the blood. 12 tissue remedies.
- *Alchemical:* The only system that separates the Quintessence and reunites it with the purified body. Homeopathy is "nearer to Alchemy than other therapies, but is still far from producing alchemical actions, inasmuch as it does not set free the quintessence which is so essential as a healing agent."
- Alchemical cure: obtained by using opposing forces of negative against positive. Ailment = negative aspect. Curative agents = positive forces. Manifestation occurs where these opposite forces meet. The object is to supplement the lacking positive forces in the human body. The *vital life force* (Prana / Quintessence) can only be separated through Alchemy — this is what sets it above all other systems.


=== Chapter V: Herbs and Stars

#doctrine[
  "Science must disprove this, if it can. Observation has also revealed that certain countries are influenced by particular planets, as astrology has long declared. As soon as certain plants are transplanted into soil foreign to their nature, they lose all or some of their curative virtues."
]

- The old hermetic axiom "As above so below, as below so above" applies here: the Macrocosmos has the same influence both on the surface as well as below the surface (tissue) of the earth as the microscopic atom.
- Plants are *transplanted* into soil foreign to their nature and lose their curative virtues — evidence that they are tied to particular planetary influences.
- *Planetary Rulerships of Body Organs* (Paracelsus):
  - Sun → Heart | Moon → Brain | Venus → Veins | Saturn → Spleen
  - Mercury → Liver | Jupiter → Lungs (chest) | Mars → Gall
  - Note: Culpeper reverses Mercury and Jupiter — stating Jupiter rules the liver and Mercury the lungs.

==== Observation: Plant Behavior as Planetary Evidence

- Chickweed flowers are open and upright from 9 AM to noon; remain closed if it rains; become pendent after rain.
- "Four-O-Clock" opens at ~4 PM.
- Dandelion (a true sundial): opens at 7 AM, closes at 5 PM.
- Pimpernel (poor man's weatherglass): closes before rain or nightfall.
- Purple sandwort: expands only when the sun shines.
- Trefoil: contracting leaves = thunder and heavy rain expected.

