Two rows of 24 cipher symbols each (numerical alchemical cipher alphabet used by the Rosicrucian fraters).


=== Chapter VII: Wisdom of the Sages — The Work Upon the Metals

==== The 1777 Rosicrucian Convention Manuscript

- Source: A rare manuscript handwritten in Latin, German script, and Rosicrucian ciphers. Originally from a monastery in Prague (Bohemia), brought to the US by the widow of Ernst Klatscher (fled during WWII). Photostatic copies obtained by AMORC and then by the PRS. A.E. Waite mentions knowledge of this document in *The Brotherhood of the Rosy Cross* (p. 457).
- Structure: Introduction (35 pages) + First Degree (Zelators, 9 pages + 4 tables) + Second Degree (Fratres Theoricus, 5 pages) + Third Degree (Practicus, 16 pages).

*First Degree (Zelators):*
- Instruction on the four alchemical elements and their symbols.
- Qabalistic material back to Solomon.
- The relationship of the triangle (signifying beginning, middle, and end) to the Four Elements.
- "One who understands thoroughly these principles of the four elements can bring forth from them the alchemical Salt, Sulphur, and Mercury." Then the student is taught how to unite these in a higher degree.
- Fundamental law of the Order: the pursuance of wisdom and virtue rather than mammon. Costs of experiments must be controlled; members work together in groups.

*Second Degree (Fratres Theoricus):*
- Theory in preparation for the next (practical) degree. May formulate their own theories but are NOT allowed to use any apparatus.
- Recommended works: Basil Valentine, Paracelsus, Henry Madathanas, Arnold de Villanova, Raymund Lully, and several anonymous alchemical writers.
- "The fire of love prepared the heavenly quintessence and eternal tincture of all souls."
- Before advancing: must know the seven planets and their metals, be familiar with minerals, rocks, ores and metals, be able to obtain pure virgin metal from ore, and know the different vessels and their uses.

*Third Degree (Practicus) — Four Processes for Menstruums:*

#lab[
  *Process I — Mineral Radical Menstruum:*
  Take equal parts saltpeter and vitriol; purify with water; drive off water by evaporation; calcine the remaining salts. (A special vitriol from outside Europe — preferably East Indies, Japan, or Mexico — was preferred, as it was stronger.) A complicated process of sublimation and distillation with these salts follows. The resulting essence can, when mixed with other metals or their salts, extract their essence.

  *Process II — Vegetable Radical Menstruum:*
  Take the best of the selected herb. Place in weak acetic acid and rectified spirits of wine, equal parts of both. Place in alembic and distil. Digest again; repeat mixture and distillation two more times (total of three). A "penitent spirit" will come over. Behind in the alembic: a small amount of dead earth and niter (saltpeter). Make 2–3 cohobations — combining the dead earth with the spirit/essence. Result: the vegetable radical menstruum. By placing other herbs in this menstruum, their essential oils can easily be obtained.

  *Process III — Animal Radical Menstruum:*
  Test the urine of a healthy person. If perfectly normal, place in alembic and distil — repeat 7 times. The remains in the alembic are mixed with the last half of the liquid obtained in the last distillation. "This substance is claimed to have an especially powerful effect when applied to sore spots on the human body." (Note: Paracelsus himself experimented with human excrement in his lectures, confounding the medical faculty.)

  *Process IV — Universal Menstruum:*
  Mix alcohol and saltpeter; distil. Take combined result; mix with one-half pound of nitrum salt by rubbing; distil again. Combine with equal portions of the above three results. Distil and sublimate 7 times. Final result = the universal essence, menstruum, or elixir.
]

- The admonition at the close of the Third Degree: all philosophical elixirs, oils, essences, alkahests, and even the Stone itself were to be used *primarily in the service of mankind and for the glory of God*. Chiefly interested in medicinal values, but also able to create enough precious stones and metals to maintain the finances of the Order. All ciphers and symbols must be mastered to avoid mistakes.

==== The Collectanea Chemica: First Matter of Metals

#doctrine[
  "All true philosophers agree that the first Matter of metals is a moist vapour, raised by the action of the central fire in the bowels of the earth, which, circulating through its pores, meets with the crude air, and is coagulated by it into an unctuous water, adhering to the earth, which serves it for a receptacle, where it is joined to a sulphur more or less pure, and a salt more or less fixing, which it attracts from the air, and, receiving a certain degree of concoction from the central and solar heat, is formed into stones and rocks, minerals and metals." — Collectanea Chemica
]

- All metals formed from the same moist vapour, varied by: different impregnations of the sperm, quality of salt and sulfur, and purity of the earth serving as matrix.
- Gold is formed when the unctuous matter (vapour joined to the fatness of sulfur) comes to places that are *subtle, pure, and moist*. Lead forms in cold and impure places. Copper: cold and pure mixed with sulfur. Silver: the vapour abounds in purity but with lesser sulfur and insufficient concoction.
- "The First Matter of metals is one thing, and not many, homogeneous, but altered by the diversity of places and sulphurs with which it is combined."
- Sendivogius called it "heavenly water, not wetting the hands; not vulgar, but almost like rain water." Hermes called it "a bird without wings" (vaporous nature) — its father is the Sun (heat), its mother the Moon (moisture); the wind carries it in its belly (air is its receptacle).
- The Seed of Metals: "the Sons of Wisdom have called their mercury... being the radical moisture of metals. This, when judiciously extracted, without corrosives, or fluxing, contains in it a seminal quality whose perfect ripeness is only in gold; in the other metals it is crude, like fruits which are yet green."
- The vital principle is invisible to the eye — but "the mind perceives it, in a true artist, as a central point of condensed air, wherein Nature, according to the will of God, has included the first principles of life in everything."
- *Where to find the seed of metals:* "it is contained in the ores of metals, as wheat is in the grain." Sown in the ore, NOT in vulgar (smelted/factitious) metals. "All these and common gold more especially, are dead." The metals the alchemist uses are *living* and have vital spirits. "Fire is the life of metals while they are still in their ore, and the fire of smelting is their death."

==== Basil Valentine: All Things Contain Vital Spirits

#doctrine[
  "You should know that all things contain operative and vital spirits which derive their substance and nourishment from their bodies; nor are the elements themselves without these spirits, whether good or evil. Men and animals have within them an operative and vitalizing spirit, and if it forsakes them, nothing but a dead body is left. Herbs and trees have spirits of health, else no art could turn them to medicinal uses. In the same way minerals and metals possess vitalizing spirits which constitute their whole strength and goodness; for what has no spirit, has no life, or vitalizing power." — Basil Valentine, Triumphal Chariot of Antimony
]

- "No animal or vegetable contains anything that can avail to fix Mercury; the attempt to do this has always ended in failure, because none of these substances have a metallic nature. Mercury is both inwardly and outwardly pure fire: therefore no fire can destroy it, no fire can change its essence; it flees from the fire, and resolves itself into an incombustible oil spiritually; but when it is once fixed, no cunning of man can volatilize it again. Then everything can by art be made of it that can be produced from gold, because after its coagulation it perfectly resembles gold, seeing that it has grown from the same root, and sprung from exactly the same branch as that precious metal." — Basil Valentine
- Note by Kerkringius (commentator on the Latin 1685 edition): "The great question which vexes all the students of our Art, 'What is Our Mercury?' is here clearly and lucidly answered."

- Valentine: All metals grow from the same root. First principle = "a mere vapour extracted from the elementary earth through the heavenly planets and, as it were, divided by the sidereal distillation of the Macrocosmos." This vapour afterwards resolves itself in the earth into water; from this *mineral water* all metals are generated. "The mineral vapour becomes this or that metal according as one or the other of the three first principles predominates — mercury, sulphur, or salt, or an unequal mixture or their weights."

==== Eirenaeus Philalethes: Open Entrance to the Closed Palace of the King
_(from The Hermetic Museum, Frankfurt, 1678)_

- On the difficulty of the First Operation: "Many Sages have complained of the tedium of our work." The preparatory part demands the most labor. "But when you have once prepared your Mercury, the most formidable part of your task is accomplished."
- Key to the path: the Sages rejected aqua fortis and all corrosive solvents after long experiments. They found the one salt "which is the first substance of all salts, which dissolves all metals and coagulates Mercury, but not without violence, whence that kind of agent is again separated entire, both in weight and virtue, from the things it is applied to."
- They discovered that Mercury's passivity "could not be remedied by any means, except the introduction of some kindred principle from without. Such a principle they discovered in metallic sulphur, which stirred up the passive sulphur in the Mercury, and by allying itself with it, expelled the aforesaid impurities."
- They found active (pure) sulphur "cunningly concealed in the *House of the Ram*." [Footnote from Albertus: "Here is the key. What planet rules Aries? What metal does this planet rule? Saturn rules what metal? Where can the sulphur be extracted from the impure Mercury? Now you have the secret unfolded."]
- The sulphur mingled with the offspring of Saturn; the doves of Venus tempered the air of Mercury; "then life was joined to life by means of the liquid; the dry was moistened; the passive was stirred into action by the active; the dead was revived by the living."
- Color progression: Nigredo (black, putrefaction complete) → Cauda Pavonis (Peacock's Tail) → perfect *green* → *white* (White Tincture, transmutes inferior metals into silver, powerful medicine) → yellow → orange / citron → fourth degree of heat → *blood-red* (thorough concoction and fitness). The vessel is then opened to reveal the matter fixed into a *ponderous scarlet mass*, easily reduced to powder, flowing like wax in fire without smoking, flaming, or loss of substance. "A few grains being taken its operation most wonderfully pervades the human body, to the extirpation of all disorders, prolonging life by its use to its utmost period" — the *Panacea*, or Universal Remedy.
- *Transmutation:* To transmute lead, melt a quantity in a clean crucible; cast in a few grains of gold filings. When melted, project a small amount of powder from the Stone. "Immediately there will arise a thick fume, which carries off with it the impurities contained in the lead, with a crackling noise, and leaves the substance of the lead transmuted into most pure gold." The small quantity of gold added serves as a medium to facilitate the transmutation.
- *Multiplication:* Dissolve the Stone in Mercury (with a few grains of pure gold dissolved in it). Process again. Repeat — each time its virtues are increased "in a ratio of ten to one hundred, to a thousand, ten thousand, etc., both in medicinal and transmuting qualities."

==== Michael Sendivogius: The New Chemical Light

#doctrine[
  "Nature is not visible, though she acts visibly; she is a volatile spirit who manifests herself in material shapes, and her existence is in the Will of God." — Sendivogius
]

- "Our science is not a dream, as the vulgar crowd imagines, or the empty invention of idle men, as the foolish suppose. It is the very truth of philosophy itself."
- Nature is *one*, true, simple, self-contained. Created by God, informed with a universal spirit. Nature is divided into four "places" in which she brings forth all things that appear — according to the good or bad quality of the place, she brings forth good or bad things. "Nothing should be made to act on that which is unlike to it."
- Students of Nature should be as Nature herself: true, simple, patient, constant. Above all, fear God and love their neighbors.
- On Seed: "Nature performs whatsoever the sperm requires of her and is, as it were, only the instrument of some artisan... the seed is the elixir of anything or its quintessence, or its most perfect digestion or decoction, or again, the Balm of Sulphur which is the same as the radical moisture in metals."
- "The seed of metals is one, but it is made to generate a great variety of things, just as the seed of man might produce a man if projected into the womb of a female of his own species, or a monstrous variety of abortions, if projected into the wombs of different female animals."
- The first matter of metals is *twofold*: (1) the moisture of air mingled with warmth = the Philosophical Mercury = "governed in the philosophical sea by the rays of the Sun and the Moon." (2) The dry heat of the earth = Sulphur.
- "Fire is the life of metals while they are still in their ore, and the fire of smelting is their death."
- Every body has a small seminal spark (its 1/8200 part) — not the whole body is seed. "You will have all you want if you find the point of Nature, which you must not look for in the vulgar metals; it is not to be found therein, for all these and common gold more especially, are dead."

==== Paracelsus: On Magisteries
_(from The Archidoxies, Book VI)_

#doctrine[
  "We speak also in like manner concerning the magisteries of herbs which, indeed, are so efficacious that half an ounce of them operates more than a hundred ounces of their body, because scarcely the hundredth part is Quintessence. So, then, the quantity thereof being so very small, a greater mass of it has to be used... One part of this being exhibited is of more avail than a hundred parts of a similar body, for this reason, because the magisteries are prepared and rendered acute to the highest degree, and are brought to a quality equal to a Quintessence in which magistery all the virtues and powers of the body are present, and from these its own helping power arises to it. For in them the penetrability and the power of the whole body exist from the mixture that is made with it." — Paracelsus
]


=== Conclusion

==== The Difference Between Chemistry and Alchemy: Two Key Points

1. No one can accomplish anything alchemically in the laboratory without the *Philosopher's Mercury* (not common metallic mercury / quicksilver).
2. The tincture (Philosopher's Mercury), including its Sulphur and feces, are to be first *separated* and then *united again* by proper processes.

- "Any poison can be removed alchemically from any herb or metal and its healing and curing properties set free. This represents another stumbling block on the road of chemistry and medical science. If only poisons could be eliminated! Very seldom is a curative agent found that has not some poisonous substances adhering to it."
- Many former alchemical secrets have become public chemical knowledge (e.g., nitric acid — once a closely guarded secret, now purchasable for a few cents). But not all alchemical knowledge has become public property.

==== Alchemy and Philosophy: The Four Elements and Quintessence

- Aristotle: ideas are *in* matter, not separated from it.
- Ancient alchemists declared only four elements that cannot be changed: fire, water, air, and earth. "H₂O is water (liquid). One may separate and analyze it, but it cannot be changed." Therefore the 100+ modern elements are better understood as atomic components — matterized, segmentary entities of cosmic consciousness manifesting in solid, liquid, or gaseous states.
- "All phenomena are threefold; there is no physical oneness. All physical manifestations, even those apparently single and individual in nature, have a threefold origin; otherwise, manifestation could not occur. This basic trinity is represented by the Philosophical Sulphur, Salt and Mercury, always constituting apparent oneness."
- "The Philosopher's Mercury is the source of all seven primary metals, as in like manner white light is the source of the seven prismatic colors." (Mercury among metals is as indigo among prismatic colors — a seventh separate factor that is neither what it appears nor fully classified.)
- The quintessence must be obtained before anything can be accomplished in Alchemy. "Can it be obtained? The answer is yes."
- Attaining the summit of alchemical knowledge — wherein cosmic consciousness is experienced as subject and the quintessentia as object — "represents man's zenith, his mastership over matter and the eventual merging into one with the Absolute, the realization of cosmic consciousness."


=== Appendix: Personal Accounts of Frater Albertus

- "When, after a long and wearisome process, the essence of gold was first extracted..." — Albertus documents personal success with the extraction of the essence of gold (golden color appearing in what was previously a clear nonacetous menstruum).
- "When the vinegar of antimony was likewise produced from the Spiessglas (glass of antimony), according to the formula of Valentine, and a red tincture produced." — This substantiated Valentine's claims that this balm of antimony would cure leprosy and ulcers with cancer; Dr. Theodore Kerckringius (Valentine's commentator and physician) had demonstrated these claims by treating a patient whose breast had been recommended for amputation.
- First extraction of essence (oil) of copper: "Such a small quantity. But how grateful we felt after proving before our own eyes what previous studies had indicated was possible. The test tube containing it is still in our possession."
- First extraction of the oil of lead.
- Recommended rare texts: *The Hermetical and Alchemical Writings of Paracelsus* (2 vols., ed. A. E. Waite), Basil Valentine's *Triumphant Chariot of Antimony*, *Collectanea Chemica*, *Turba Philosophorum*, *The New Pearl of Great Price* by Bonus of Ferrara, writings of Franz Hartmann, *Secret Symbols of the Rosicrucians of the Sixteenth and Seventeenth Centuries* (Geheime Figuren..., Altona, 1785–88, 2 vols.), and *Alchemy Rediscovered and Restored* by Archibald Cockren.


=== The Alchemical Manifesto (1960)

The Manifesto addresses why the Paracelsus Research Society (PRS) operated under specific constraints:

- *Why no public street address:* As in former times, the quarters are not designed to make themselves known to the general public. Publicity would only result in misrepresentation.
- *Why no named representatives:* No true alchemist seeks fame. Personal acknowledgment "could lead, with some, to a personality cult, and this is entirely irrelevant. The work itself is the important thing, never personalities."
- *Why no memberships:* Alchemical aspirants should be free — "free in their thinking and free in their actions." There is a right time and place for group obligations, and students are likely already members of fraternal organizations designed for that activity.
- *Why bulletins are received by those who have done little lab work:* Either a previous contact with the work had been established, or the individual may contact another person who is ready. Contacts are made at times in strange ways.
- *On isolation / "alchemical communes":* Rejected entirely. "Our work is here among mankind. Amidst the hustle and bustle of everyday life is the place for us to overcome the shortcomings still adhering to us as humans."
- *On advanced retreats:* Advanced students may be given an opportunity to conceal themselves for a *period of seven weeks at the utmost* in a retreat in a high mountainous place in the western US. Never more than twelve aspirants at one time. Absolutely free of charge. Solely on spiritual merit — no restriction on social, racial, religious, fraternal, financial, or educational standing.
- *The closing charge:* "Since this work is of an unselfish nature... May the Cosmic Light guide and direct you in your sincere endeavors, and may you be one of those to glorify the works of the Divine by becoming an administrator of the heavenly bounties among mankind."

#safety[
  - *Never* use denatured alcohol or methanol — these are poisonous, both to the body and to the alchemical life force.
  - The Soxhlet extraction must use a *water bath*, not a direct open flame, or the delicate Sulfur (oil) will be scorched and lose its efficacy.
  - Calcination of the feces: the alcohol-soaked herb ignites immediately — this is an outdoor activity due to smoke and odor.
  - The elixir should *never be taken undiluted* — due to its condensed potency and raised vibratory rate. A few grains dissolved in a full glass of water or wine.
  - Do not attempt the Greater Circulation (mineral / metallic work) until the herbal process has been fully mastered. "Plants are much more forgiving of mistakes and accidents."
  - Maintain the correct intent throughout: "the state of the operator's mind ('The Interior Lab') is as important as the temperature of the furnace." Purified materials at a certain stage become susceptible to mental impressions — good or bad — from those around them.
]
